df_games = pd.read_csv('/datasets/games.csv')

The purpose of this project is to examine data on game sales and identify patterns that will help advertisers improve future sales. I will prepare the data by looking for missing values and other problems before formatting it for analysis. I will explore how game characteristics (e.g., platform, genre, rating, and reviews) impact global and regional sales. Finally, I will conduct statistical tests addressing key questions about specific platforms and genres.

    print()
    display(df[col].value_counts())

# Compare non-missing, missing, and tbd data in user_score column

tbds = df_games[df_games['user_score'] == 'tbd']
missing = df_games[df_games['user_score'].isna()]
not_missing_or_tbd = df_games[(~df_games['user_score'].isna()) & (df_games['user_score'] != 'tbd')]

display(pd.DataFrame({'user_score': ['not missing or tbd', 'missing', 'tbd', 'total'],
                      'count': [len(not_missing_or_tbd), len(missing), len(tbds), len(df_games)],
                      'percent': [100*len(not_missing_or_tbd)/len(df_games), 100*len(missing)/len(df_games), 100*len(tbds)/len(df_games), 100]
                    }))
print()

for col in ['year_of_release', 'na_sales', 'eu_sales', 'jp_sales', 'other_sales', 'critic_score']:
    print(f'Descriptives of {col} for values of user_score:')
    descriptives = pd.concat([not_missing_or_tbd[col].describe(), missing[col].describe()], axis=1)
    descriptives = pd.concat([descriptives, tbds[col].describe()], axis=1)
    descriptives.columns = ['not missing or tbd', 'missing', 'tbd']

    display(descriptives)
    print()

for col in ['platform', 'genre', 'rating']:
    tbd_values = tbds[col].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
    missing_values = missing[col].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
    not_missing_or_tbd_values = not_missing_or_tbd[col].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
    values = pd.concat([not_missing_or_tbd_values, missing_values, tbd_values], axis=1)
    values.columns = ['not missing or tbd', 'missing', 'tbd']

    print(f'Percentages for each unique value of {col} for values of user_score:')
    display(values)
    print()

Values of "tbd" appear 2,424 times in the user_score column and nowhere else. For the user_score column, 40% of rows are missing and 15% are tbds, but nothing obviously distinguishes them from regular rows (neither tbd nor missing). Tbd rows have comparable year_of_release values, slightly lower critic_scores, and considerably lower sales than regular and missing rows.


For na_sales, eu_sales, and other_sales, values in regular rows are a little more than twice as large as those in missing rows, which are a little less than twice as large as those in tbd rows. The pattern is different for jp_sales where values in missing rows are twice as large as those in regular rows and 46 times as large as those in tbd rows.


Tbd rows are low on PS2, X360, PS3, PC, and PS4 platforms (all Sony or Microsoft) and high on Wii, DS, and GBA (all Nintendo). Whereas tbd rows are low on Shooter, Role-Player, and Fighting genres and T and M ratings, they are high on Misc and Puzzle genres and E ratings.


Tbds seem to be predominantly games made by Nintendo, marketed for kids, and low in violence. Since those categories overlap and the relevant differences are not sharp, I still cannot say which is most important. Tbds also appear to be either unpopular or unreleased in Japan. That offers an interesting profile of tbds, but offers no guidance on what to do with them. I will convert "tbd" to NaN and treat it like other missing data.

Thousands of values are missing in the critic_score, user_score, and rating columns, 269 are missing in the year_of_release column, and 2 rows are missing values in both the name and genre columns. The two rows without name and genre are also missing score and rating data but they do contain sales data, so I will keep them for that purpose. I do not see any obvious patterns to explain the missing values in year_of_release, so I will assume they are random.


A group of 6,621 rows with missing values in all three of the evaluative columns represents 77% of the 8,578 missing values in critic_score and 99% of the 6,701 and 6,667 missing values in user_score and rating, respectively. Withing finding any obvious patterns, I will assume the remaining missing values in those columns are random and I will refer to the 6,621 rows missing all three as "unjudged." Although 55% of tbd rows are missing critic_scores, only 46 of them are unjudged, so I will ignore tbds going forward.

# Compare unjudged rows to the rest

unjudged = df_games[df_games['unjudged'] == 1]
judged = df_games[df_games['unjudged'] == 0]
unjudged = unjudged[unjudged['user_score'] != 'tbd']
judged = judged[judged['user_score'] != 'tbd']

for col in ['year_of_release', 'na_sales', 'eu_sales', 'jp_sales', 'other_sales']:
    unjudged_col = unjudged[col].astype(float)
    judged_col = judged[col].astype(float)
    descriptives = pd.concat([judged_col.describe(), unjudged_col.describe()], axis=1)
    descriptives.columns = [f'judged', f'unjudged']
    test = st.ttest_ind(unjudged_col, judged_col, equal_var=False, nan_policy='omit')

    print(col)
    display(descriptives[:3].T)
    print()

for col in ['platform', 'genre']:
    unjudged_values = unjudged[col].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
    judged_values = judged[col].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
    values = pd.concat([judged_values, unjudged_values], axis=1).dropna()
    values.columns = ['judged', 'unjudged']
    values['ratio (j/u)'] = values['judged'] / values['unjudged']
    values['ratio (u/j)'] = 1 / values['ratio (j/u)']

    print(f'{col}:')
    display(values)
    print()

Compared to the others, unjudged rows have slightly lower values in year_of_release and values twice as high in jp_sales but less than half as high in the other three sales columns (na_sales, eu_sales, and other_sales). PS, DC, and PSV consoles and Adventure and Misc genres are at least twice as common in unjudged rows as in the rest, and XB, PC, X360, GC, XOne, and WiiU consoles and the Shooter genre are less than half as common. I fail to see any helpful patterns except that games in the unjudged rows sell well in Japan and nowhere else.


Between the tbds and unjudged, something is going on with Japan in this dataset, but I still have not put it together. The critic_score, user_score, and rating data probably all came from a separate smaller dataset, hence the overlapping missing values. There might well be a reason the smaller dataset is missing 40% of the games in the full dataset. Maybe the missing games were primarily sold in Japan or to Japanese speakers and not covered by the US-based website aggregating scores and ratings. I have no way to confirm that with these data and it also has no bearing on how I should treat the missing values.


I prefer to retain as much data as possible by deleting missing values pairwise only when necessary, so I will not delete any rows. I also prefer to avoid fabricating data by routinely imputing missing values. If a row is missing the critic score, for example, I have no reason to believe much less assert that it should be the column mean. I will leave the missing data as it is but I will convert year_of_release and critic_score columns to a nullable integer data type for easier processing. I will also replace "tbd" values in user_score with NaNs and change that column to a float data type. Finally, I will delete the superfluous unjudged column.

# Check before converting float columns to Int64

def check_float_for_int(df, column):
    mask = df[column].notna()
    are_integers = np.all(np.floor(df[column][mask]) == df[column][mask])
    
    if are_integers:
        print(f"All non-missing values in the {column} column are integers: proceed to convert")
    else: 
        print(f"Some non-missing values in the {column} column are not integers: DO NOT convert")
    
check_float_for_int(df_games, 'year_of_release')
check_float_for_int(df_games, 'critic_score')
check_float_for_int(df_games, 'user_score')

For PS4 games, total sales is significantly correlated with critic score (r = 0.41, p < 0.05) but not user score (r = -0.03, p = 0.61). The scatterplot makes it clear that games with higher critic scores also have higher total sales, but we must resist attributing causality. Critics might prefer well-selling games, consumers might buy well-reviewed games, or both critic scores and sales might reflect a third variable such as game quality or marketing.

# Create a function to compare the sales of the same games on other platforms

def reviews_by_sales_for_platform(df, platform):
    platform_games = df[df['platform'] == platform]
    platform_games.plot(x='critic_score', y='total_sales', kind='scatter', xlabel='Critic Score', ylabel='Sales in USD Million', title=f'Global Sales for {platform} by Critic Score')
    platform_games.plot(x='user_score', y='total_sales', kind='scatter', xlabel='User Score', ylabel='Sales in USD Million', title=f'Global Sales for {platform}  by User Score')

    for col in ['critic_score', 'user_score']:
        df_dropped = platform_games[['platform','total_sales', col]].dropna()
        r, p = st.pearsonr(df_dropped['total_sales'], df_dropped[col])
        print(f'Correlation between total_sales and {col} for {platform}')
        print(f'Correlation coefficient: {r:.2f}, P-value: {p:.4f}')
        print()

# Create a function to examine total regional sales 

def examine_regional_sales(df, region, column):
    df_grouped = df.groupby(column)[f'{region}_sales'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)

    display(df_grouped)

    plt.bar(df_grouped.index, df_grouped.values)
    plt.xlabel(column)
    plt.ylabel('Sales in USD million')
    plt.title(f'Total {region}_sales by {column} Since 2008')
    plt.xticks(rotation=60)
    plt.show()

        region_list.append(market_share)
    platform_dict[platform] = region_list
platform_market_share = pd.DataFrame(platform_dict).T
platform_market_share.columns = regions

# Test the hypothesis that the average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are different

print("Independent t-test comparing user_score for Action and Sports genres:")
print(f"t-statistic: {st.ttest_ind(Action_user_scores, Sports_user_scores, equal_var=False)[0]:.2f}")
print(f"p-value: {st.ttest_ind(Action_user_scores, Sports_user_scores, equal_var=False)[1]:.4f}")

























Independent t-test comparing user_score for Action and Sports genres:
t-statistic: 10.23
p-value: 0.0000

























Null Hypothesis: Action and Sports genres have equal user scores

Alternative Hypothesis: Action and Sports genres have different user scores

Statistical Test: Independent t-test with alpha = 0.05 and equal variances not assumed

Conclusion: We can reject the null hypothesis (t = 10.23, p < 0.05)






















I conclude that user ratings are significantly higher for the Action genre than for the Sports genre, but XOne and PC platforms are not significanlty different.


For both of these tests, I formulated the null and alternative hypotheses in the same way they are always formulated: the null hypothesis posits no difference between conditions and the alternative hypothesis posits a difference between conditions. I also chose the standard significance level used across the social sciences: alpha = 0.05. I did not assume equal variances for either t-test because of significant (p < 0.05) Levene's tests for both sets of data.






















General Discussion






















I began by preparing the data, making a few formatting adjustments, and investigating missing values. I found a large segment of data (6,621 rows) simultaneously missing values in the critic_score, user_score, and rating columns. Besides selling well only in Japan, nothing obviously distinguishes those rows from the rest. My best guess is that the critic_score, user_score, and rating columns came from a smaller dataset separate from the rest of the columns, maybe one that excluded certain Japanese games. There are also 2,424 rows with "tbd" for user_score. They tend to be poor-selling games predominantly made by Nintendo, marketed for kids, and low in violence. Without a good explanation for them, I treated them like other missing data.


Several columns have relatively small numbers of additional missing values (2 for name, 2 for genre, 80 for user_score, 145 for rating, 269 for year_of_release, and 1,957 for critic_score) that show no obvious patterns. I tried to use all the data available but no more, neither deleting nor arbitrarily filling missing values. I replaced NaN values in the rating column with "unknown" to track those in later analyses. The lifetime of a top-selling platform is less than a decade (9.6 years) and the best sellers in the full dataset (PS3 and X360) are quite old. In estimating 2017 sales, I tried to exclude obsolete trends by dropping data from before 2013.


The best-selling platforms in recent years were PS4 and XOne. Global sales was declining for every platform in 2016, but PS4, 3DS, WiiU, and XOne had strong sales while Wii, X360, PC, PS3, and PSV were rapidly dwindling. Reviews are significantly correlated with global sales for top-selling games, with critic score consistently a better predictor than user score. Shooter games make the most money on average, Action games sell the most overall because there are so many, Platform games are lucrative but rare, and Sports games are a good middle ground with solid margins and volume. Simulation, Strategy, and Puzzle games, on the other hand, are all poor sellers.


I created profiles for the North American, European, and Japanese markets. Whereas North America prefers Microsoft consoles and Europe prefers Sony consoles, Japan prefers portable Nintendo platforms more and Microsoft less than the rest. Every region enjoys Action games, but North America and Europe also like Shooter games while Japan prefers Role-Playing games. Games rated M (Mature) are the best sellers in North America and Europe but unknown ratings dominate Japan where a different rating system prevails.


Statistical tests reveal that user scores are significantly higher for Action than Sports genres but not significantly different for XOne and PC platforms.


The purpose of this project is to determine what would make a game sell well in 2017 according to indicators in the dataset and I came to a few potentially useful conclusions. Although the heyday of massive PS3 and X360 sales has passed, the current generation (PS4, 3DS, WiiU, and XOne) is still going strong. Advertising should focus on those newer platforms and the Shooter, Sports, and Platform genres while minimizing the Simulation, Strategy, and Puzzle genres. They should also prioritize games with high critic scores, maybe even including the scores in ads in case the effect is causal. Advertising should emphasize Microsoft, Shooter, and rated-M games in in North America; Sony, Shooter, and rated-M games in Europe; and portable Nintendo and Role-Playing games in Japan.
